{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8709955a-8360-4f1a-8af1-3a20b07b1f72","content":"## `UseLegacyV2RuntimeActivationPolicy`\n\nWhen this flag is set to `1` (via `<startup useLegacyV2RuntimeActivationPolicy=\"true\">`), it changes how the CLR activates legacy COM components and mixed-mode assemblies:\n\n**What it does:**\n- Binds CLR v2 (`.NET 2.0/3.5`) COM activation requests to the runtime specified in `<supportedRuntime>` (typically v4.0) instead of loading CLR v2.\n- Effectively forces legacy mixed-mode C++/CLI assemblies and COM components to load into the v4 runtime.\n\n**Without it (default):**\n- COM activation of v2-targeted components loads CLR v2 side-by-side with v4, which can cause conflicts or failures if v2 isn't installed.\n\n**With it enabled:**\n- Only the v4 runtime is loaded; v2-era components run under v4's compatibility mode.\n- Avoids side-by-side CLR loading in the same process.\n\n**Common scenario:** You'll see this when hosting legacy plugins, Office add-ins, or mixed-mode C++/CLI DLLs in a .NET 4+ process.\n\n**Typical config:**\n```xml\n<configuration>\n  <startup useLegacyV2RuntimeActivationPolicy=\"true\">\n    <supportedRuntime version=\"v4.0\" />\n  </startup>\n</configuration>\n```\n\n**Caveat:** This is a .NET Framework–only concept; it has no effect in .NET Core / .NET 5+.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6f68ac83-4012-49a4-b36f-1180ad65df99","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a CLR (Common Language Runtime) activation log message related to `UseLegacyV2RuntimeActivationPolicy`. This is a .NET Framework question about runtime activation behavior. Let me answer from my knowledge.","outputTokens":438},"id":"f317b821-19c2-4b60-951e-28dfdf9ed6dc","timestamp":"2026-04-08T01:12:33.691Z","parentId":"a06368e7-e4e3-4872-87d5-03a01d6e1523"}
